{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645172","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645172"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:13:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:13:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18087"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18087"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.86,0.05,0,0,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10801"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74085"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10801"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18087"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59561"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5375"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5723"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25155"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25548"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74085"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA parent brings their healthy two-year-old child to a medical clinic requesting an elective cosmetic procedure that would permanently alter the child\u0027s appearance. The procedure carries some surgical risks but is not medically necessary.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the ethical principle that would guide decision-making in this situation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Protection of the child\u0027s right to an open future","Immediate benefit outweighs future considerations","Medical paternalism should determine outcomes","Social conformity justifies early intervention","Parental autonomy takes precedence over all other considerations"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ethical principle of \u003Cstrong\u003Eprotection of the child\u0027s right to an open future\u003C/strong\u003E is most relevant here. This principle holds that children have a right to reach maturity with their key life choices preserved, allowing them to make autonomous decisions about their own body and identity when they are capable of doing so.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate benefit outweighs future considerations\u003C/strong\u003E - For non-therapeutic procedures, the potential future autonomy of the child should be prioritised over any immediate cosmetic benefits.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedical paternalism should determine outcomes\u003C/strong\u003E - Contemporary medical ethics emphasises patient autonomy and shared decision-making rather than paternalistic approaches.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESocial conformity justifies early intervention\u003C/strong\u003E - Social pressures or cultural norms alone do not provide sufficient ethical justification for performing irreversible procedures on children.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParental autonomy takes precedence over all other considerations\u003C/strong\u003E - While parents have significant decision-making authority, this is not absolute and must be balanced against the child\u0027s future interests, particularly for non-therapeutic interventions.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe principle of open future is particularly important for elective procedures that permanently alter a child\u0027s body or limit their future choices. Unless there is a clear medical necessity, such decisions should be delayed until the child can participate in the decision-making process.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The principle of open future protects a child\u0027s right to make autonomous decisions about their life when they reach maturity.","Medical decisions that permanently limit future choices should be delayed until the child can participate in decision-making.","Non-therapeutic interventions that irreversibly alter a child\u0027s body require strong justification."],"references":["Mandal J, Ponnambath DK, Parija SC. Bioethics: A brief review. Trop Parasitol. 2017;7(1):5-7. doi:10.4103/tp.TP_4_17","Varkey B. Principles of Clinical Ethics and Their Application to Practice. Med Princ Pract. 2021;30(1):17-28. doi:10.1159/000509119"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59561"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18087"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59561"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T11:44:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T11:45:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10801"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74085"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships